[{"data":1,"prerenderedAt":1239},["ShallowReactive",2],{"header-locale:\u002Fen\u002Fmisc\u002F2023\u002F03\u002F07\u002Ffrontend-mock-api-with-mockoon\u002F":3,"page:\u002Fen\u002Fmisc\u002F2023\u002F03\u002F07\u002Ffrontend-mock-api-with-mockoon\u002F":4,"alt:\u002Fen\u002Fmisc\u002F2023\u002F03\u002F07\u002Ffrontend-mock-api-with-mockoon\u002F":3,"prev-next:\u002Fen\u002Fmisc\u002F2023\u002F03\u002F07\u002Ffrontend-mock-api-with-mockoon\u002F":1215,"related:\u002Fen\u002Fmisc\u002F2023\u002F03\u002F07\u002Ffrontend-mock-api-with-mockoon\u002F":1224},"\u002Fother\u002F20230307\u002F1852899605\u002F",{"id":5,"title":6,"abbrlink":7,"altUrl":3,"body":8,"category":1197,"date":1198,"description":1199,"extension":125,"lang":1200,"meta":1201,"navigation":168,"path":1202,"readingMinutes":1203,"seo":1204,"standalone":1205,"stem":1206,"tags":1207,"tldr":1212,"updated":1198,"url":1213,"__hash__":1214},"content\u002Fen\u002FMisc\u002Ffrontend-mock-api-with-mockoon.md","A Mock API Skill Every Frontend Dev Should Have: Try Mockoon","5096482731",{"type":9,"value":10,"toc":1184},"minimark",[11,19,24,27,31,39,42,45,51,56,61,64,68,71,82,87,95,98,104,107,113,117,120,499,502,507,510,516,519,525,528,533,540,545,548,554,558,561,567,571,574,580,583,596,599,602,608,611,617,620,625,628,634,638,641,646,650,653,659,662,666,669,675,678,684,688,691,697,700,705,708,712,715,868,871,877,880,886,889,893,906,913,1010,1013,1106,1109,1115,1118,1150,1159,1163,1166,1173,1177,1180],[12,13,14],"p",{},[15,16],"img",{"alt":17,"src":18},"Mockoon","https:\u002F\u002Fimages.israynotarray.com\u002FblogImg\u002Fother\u002Fmockoon\u002Fhp-hero.png",[20,21,23],"h2",{"id":22},"intro","Intro",[12,25,26],{},"For frontend devs — junior or senior — knowing how to use a Mock API is genuinely worth it. This post walks through Mockoon, my go-to Mock API tool.",[20,28,30],{"id":29},"why-learn-mock-apis","Why learn Mock APIs",[12,32,33,34,38],{},"Mock API basically means ",[35,36,37],"strong",{},"simulated API",". Why simulate? Let me set a scene with a realistic dev situation.",[12,40,41],{},"You've got a feature with 7 days to ship — frontend and backend both needed. The backend says they'll have endpoints ready in 5–6 days. You estimate your work (UI + API integration) at 5–6 days too. Question — as the frontend dev, can you really wait until backend ships endpoints before you start integrating?",[12,43,44],{},"Of course not. Integrating always has its own friction — endpoints that don't respond, missing fields, mismatched shapes — so you're going to need to keep talking to the backend as you go. If you wait, the deadline's blown. And we haven't even reserved 1–2 days for testing yet.",[12,46,47],{},[15,48],{"alt":49,"src":50},"Deadline","https:\u002F\u002Fi.imgur.com\u002FNyJk7JL.png",[12,52,53],{},[15,54],{"alt":49,"src":55},"https:\u002F\u002Fi.imgur.com\u002FJSdWq4X.png",[12,57,58],{},[15,59],{"alt":49,"src":60},"https:\u002F\u002Fi.imgur.com\u002FCgEEAc6.png",[12,62,63],{},"This is where Mock API pays off. You ask the backend to ship the API spec first — URL, method, request params, response shape — and you turn that spec into a Mock API. Now once your UI is done, you start integrating immediately, while the backend keeps building the real endpoints. Both sides work in parallel, frontend isn't blocked. It's a pretty solid workflow.",[20,65,67],{"id":66},"what-is-mockoon","What is Mockoon",[12,69,70],{},"Mock API is a concept; there are lots of tools to implement it — Postman, Mocky, MockServer, Mockoon, etc. This post focuses on Mockoon, which is what I use.",[12,72,73,74,81],{},"Head to the ",[75,76,80],"a",{"href":77,"rel":78},"https:\u002F\u002Fmockoon.com\u002F",[79],"nofollow","Mockoon website",", grab the installer for your OS, and install it.",[12,83,84],{},[15,85],{"alt":17,"src":86},"https:\u002F\u002Fimages.israynotarray.com\u002FblogImg\u002Fother\u002Fmockoon\u002F%E6%88%AA%E5%9C%96%202023-03-07%2016.00.26.png",[12,88,89,90,94],{},"(Download page: ",[75,91,92],{"href":92,"rel":93},"https:\u002F\u002Fmockoon.com\u002Fdownload\u002F",[79],")",[12,96,97],{},"First time you open Mockoon, you'll see this:",[12,99,100],{},[15,101],{"alt":102,"src":103},"Welcome new Mockoon user","https:\u002F\u002Fimages.israynotarray.com\u002FblogImg\u002Fother\u002Fmockoon\u002F%E6%88%AA%E5%9C%96%202023-03-07%2016.17.21.png",[12,105,106],{},"Click \"Start using Mockoon\" and you're in.",[12,108,109],{},[15,110],{"alt":111,"src":112},"Start","https:\u002F\u002Fimages.israynotarray.com\u002FblogImg\u002Fother\u002Fmockoon\u002F%E6%88%AA%E5%9C%96%202023-03-07%2016.20.46.png",[20,114,116],{"id":115},"using-mockoon","Using Mockoon",[12,118,119],{},"Mockoon ships with a demo API, but let's actually walk through building one. Say I'm the backend and I hand you this TodoList API spec:",[121,122,127],"pre",{"className":123,"code":124,"language":125,"meta":126,"style":126},"language-md shiki shiki-themes github-dark-high-contrast","# Name: Get todo list\n## API URL: \u002Fapi\u002Fv1\u002Ftodos\n## Method: GET\n## Request: none\n## Response:\n\n[\n  {\n    \"id\": 1,\n    \"title\": \"Todo 1\",\n    \"completed\": false\n  },\n  {\n    \"id\": 2,\n    \"title\": \"Todo 2\",\n    \"completed\": true\n  }\n]\n\n---\n\n# Name: Create a todo\n## API URL: \u002Fapi\u002Fv1\u002Ftodos\n## Method: POST\n## Request:\n\n{\n  \"title\": \"Todo 3\",\n  \"completed\": false\n}\n\n## Response:\n\n{\n  \"message\": \"Created successfully\"\n}\n\n---\n\n# Name: Update a todo\n## API URL: \u002Fapi\u002Fv1\u002Ftodos\u002F:id\n## Method: PUT\n## Request:\n\n{\n  \"title\": \"Todo 3\",\n  \"completed\": true\n}\n\n## Response:\n\n{\n  \"message\": \"Updated successfully\"\n}\n\n---\n\n# Name: Delete a todo\n## API URL: \u002Fapi\u002Fv1\u002Ftodos\u002F:id\n## Method: DELETE\n## Request: none\n## Response:\n\n{\n  \"message\": \"Deleted successfully\"\n}\n\n","md","",[128,129,130,139,145,151,157,163,170,177,183,189,195,201,207,212,218,224,230,236,242,247,253,258,264,269,